  "prompt": "Which one is grammatically correct: pick up someone at the airport or from the airport?",
  "response": "Both \"pick up someone at the airport\" and \"pick up someone from the airport\" are grammatically correct, but they convey slightly different nuances.\n\n- \"Pick up someone at the airport\" emphasizes the location where the action of picking up will occur. It suggests that you will go to the airport to pick up the person.\n\n- \"Pick up someone from the airport\" emphasizes the origin of the person being picked up. It suggests that the person is coming from the airport and you will be picking them up.\n\nIn most contexts, \"pick up someone at the airport\" is more commonly used.",
